Topic Models Up & Down!

Theresa Gessler, Ece Kural, Gino Pauselli, Martin Riedl, Jiyoun Suk

3 August 2018

The Problem

We often use topic models to get an overview of our corpus - but do topic models actually represent what humans think of as topics?

We use a generic corpus to assess this question.

The Corpus

We use a corpus from the sun, a British Boulevard newspaper, that contains a total of xxx articles published between December 2017 and July 2018. We restrict our sample to articles published in the news section, leaving us with 22806 articles after throwing out articles without text. Below, we present the number of news articles per day to give you an overview, though for now we dont address time variation.

Finding Topics bottom-up

Before running unsupervised methods to get an overview of our corpus, we wanted to get an overview ourselves. Similar to generating a manually annotated training sample, we annotated a randomly selected subset of documents. However, our selection we selected only 100 documents.

Below, we present our manual method of topic generation and its results. We call this TJOPIC: Topical JOurnalism Politics International Relations Classification.

Procedure

Each of us had the same task:

  • read the first 20 documents, identify what you think of as a topic
  • (as group) discuss if 15 may be an appropriate number
  • read remaining 80 documents
  • decide on topics
  • attribute documents to topics
  • determine 5 keywords per topic
    • this could be done in an automated word by checking for words that have high tf-idf scores in our documents
    • but in such a small sample, human choice seemed more effective
  • (as group) discuss what we thought of as a topic
  • (as group) decide on a common set of topics and keywords for further iterations
    • originally, we were planning to do our analysis for each teammembers topic model - but we ran out of computing power for that

Getting into information retrieval

Now that we have decided on our topics of interest - how do we find them without coding thousands of articles? We outline TJOPIC_x, a method to extract topic shares with our keywords based on theories of information retrieval. TJOPIC_x20 relies on a larger set of keywords, with additional terms generated via keyness statistics of the least and most relevant documents.

The Vector Space model

For this, we rely on the vector space model of text

Documents and queries are represented as vectors.

\(d_j = ( w_{1,j} ,w_{2,j} , \dotsc ,w_{t,j} )\)

\(q = ( w_{1,q} ,w_{2,q} , \dotsc ,w_{n,q} )\)

Each Dimension corresponds to a separate term. If a term occurs in the document, its value in the vector is non-zero. Several different ways of computing these values, also known as (term) weights, have been developed. We use tf-idf, that is term-frequency-inverse-document-frequency to weigh those words higher that are unique to specific documents.

Advantages of vector space models

  • simple model based on linear algebra
  • continuous degree of similarity between queries & doucments - this allows a better comparison to LDA results
  • allows ranking of documents according to relevance
  • takes into account all our search terms (advantage over e.g.collocations or simple tf-idf)
  • allows partial matching

Limitations of vector space models

  • long documents have smaller similarity values - but our documents are short
  • semantic sensitivity: documents with similar context but different vocabulary wont be associated
    • expansions with wordembeddings or synonyms from WordNet may overcome this
  • weighting is intuitive but not mathematically derived
  • assumption of word independence violated maybe an overly simplified model of speech

Writing our own Search Engine

Now, we create our search engine. We load our data - we will generate the dfm again from scratch. We do text preprocessing in quanteda, the actual search engine in tm so we convert our dfm into a document-term matrix

load("C:/Users/theresa/Desktop/miniproject/news.RData")
news_only <-subset(news_only,is.na(news_only$`_source.text`)==F)
news_only$text<-news_only$`_source.text`
joined_df<-dplyr::bind_rows(news_only,queries)
full_corpus<-corpus(joined_df)
full_tokens<-tokens(full_corpus,remove_numbers=T,remove_punct=T)
full_dfm<-dfm(full_tokens,stem=T)
full_dfm<-dfm_remove(full_dfm,stopwords("en"))
full_dfm<-dfm_trim(full_dfm,min_docfreq = 228)

full_tm<-convert(full_dfm,"tm")

Now we transpose this into a Term-Document Matrix

term.doc.matrix.stm<-as.TermDocumentMatrix(t(full_tm), weighting = weightTf)

First, we define some utility functions we will make use of:

  • tf-idf weights from term frequency and document frequency
  • getting weights per term from tf-idf weights
  • store a variable with number of documents
get.tf.idf.weights <- function(tf.vec, df) {
  weight = rep(0, length(tf.vec))
  weight[tf.vec > 0] = (1 + log2(tf.vec[tf.vec > 0])) * log2(N.docs/df)
  weight
}

get.weights.per.term.vec <- function(tfidf.row) {
  term.df <- sum(tfidf.row[1:N.docs] > 0)
  tf.idf.vec <- get.tf.idf.weights(tfidf.row, term.df)
  return(tf.idf.vec)
}
N.docs<-length(news_only$text)
N.queries<-length(topics)

Now we are all set to calculate the tfidf Matrix and get the most relevant documents for our set of keywords.

tfidf.matrix <- t(apply(term.doc.matrix.stm, c(1), FUN = get.weights.per.term.vec))
tfidf.matrix <- scale(tfidf.matrix, center = FALSE, scale = sqrt(colSums(tfidf.matrix^2)))

doc.vector <- tfidf.matrix[, 1:N.docs]
doc.scores<-list(0)

for (i in 1:length(topics)) {
  query.vector <- tfidf.matrix[, (N.docs+i)]
  doc.scores[[i]] <- t(query.vector) %*% doc.vector
}
results_mat<-matrix(unlist(doc.scores),ncol=length(topics),dimnames=list(1:N.docs,topics))
results_mat<-cbind(results_mat,news_only$`_source.title`,news_only$`_source.text`)
save(results_mat,file="results.RData")
results_df <- data.frame(results_mat)
save(results_df,file="results_df.RData")

Comparison with LDA

How do our results compare to LDA?

We calculate an LDA topic model as implemented in the topicmodel package.

text_corpus

k <- 15
control_LDA_Gibbs <- list(alpha = 12/k, estimate.beta = T,
                          verbose = 0, prefix = tempfile(), 
                          save = 0, keep = 50, 
                          seed = 980, 
                          nstart = 1, best = T, 
                          delta = 0.1, 
                          iter = 100, 
                          burnin = 10) 


set.seed(123)
text_lda_15 <- LDA(documents, k, method = "Gibbs", control = control_LDA_Gibbs) #this is the one

terms(text_lda_15, 10)
terms <- as.data.frame(terms(text_lda_15,50))
write.csv(terms, "ldaout.terms.csv")
text_lda_topics <- topics(text_lda_15)
lda.topics <- as.data.frame(text_lda_topics)
write.csv(lda.topics, "ldaout.topics.csv")
